The fission events were counted using parallel-

samples were placed on a cathode plate kept at
The experiment was carried out at
spallation of protons on a bare tungsten target. The
experiment was located at a 90-deg station (4FP90L
flight path). The proton beam delivered to WNR was
bunched and chopped to produce pulse trains -
nominally spaced by 1.8 ms. The macropulses are
delivered at a repetition rate of 40 Hz and are 675
mu-s in duration, resulting in about 375 micropulses
per macropulse The 4FP90L flight path has a beam stop
located 25 m downstream from the detector, a
sufficient distance to minimize neutron backscatter.
The neutron TOF is calibrated using the
photofission peak (which results from fission induced
by spallation gamma rays) and by beam filters. The
photofission peak position is used to extract the TOF
offset and gain, and its width provides a measure of
the timing resolution of the full system.
